Pleadings are statements of the case of the pleading party, to be admitted or denied by the opposite side, and not positive allegations of the truth of their contents: Jamieson v R (1993) 177 CLR 574;  116 ALR 193;  [1993] HCA 48;  BC9303581  (although they may involve an implied representation that the case is genuinely put: Gray v Hedigan  (FCA, Burchett, Foster and O’Loughlin JJ, 6 October 1994, unreported, BC9400267)). Accordingly, allegations contained in pleadings are not admissible as an admission against the party filing them: Boileau v Rutlin (1848) 2 LJ Ex 665 at 679–81; 154 ER 657 at 663; Buckmaster v Meiklejohn (1853) 8 Exch 634 at 637; 155 ER 1506 at 1507 ; McKinlay v North Australian Co (1869) 3 SALR 135 at 139 ; Austin v Austin [1905] VLR 564 at 566–7; (1905) 11 ALR 337 ; Kleeners Pty Ltd v Lee Tim (1959) 78 WN (NSW) 746 at 747–8 ; British Thomson-Houston Co Ltd v British Insulated and Helsby Cables Ltd [1924] 1 Ch 203  (on appeal); British Thomson-Houston Co Ltd v British Insulated and Helsby Cables Ltd [1924] 2 Ch 160; (evidence adduced in earlier proceedings, but not the subject of a specific finding, is not admissible as an admission in later proceedings); Stohl Aviation v Electrum Finance Pty Ltd (1984) 5 FCR 187; 56 ALR 716 ; Pearce v Hall (1989) 52 SASR 568 ; Laws v Australian Broadcasting Tribunal (1990) 170 CLR 70 at 85–6, 98; 93 ALR 435;  BC9002913 ; Singleton v John Fairfax & Sons Ltd [1982] 2 NSWLR 38 at 50  (a defamation action in which Hunt J expressed the view that pleadings could not be placed in a special category and that whether or not allegations in pleadings constituted an admission depended upon a consideration of all the circumstances including in particular the context in which the allegation was made, a view which was rejected by the High Court in Laws v Australian Broadcasting Tribunal
, above,  at CLR 86. Where pleadings are verified by affidavit (as is required by 
r 14.23
 or 
r 14.24
), it may well be that the verifying affidavit could properly be construed as containing relevant admissions against the pleading party, a point apparently left open in Laws v Australian Broadcasting Tribunal, above,  at CLR 85. However, since verification relates only to matters of fact, no admission would attach to allegations that were either matters of law or matters of mixed law and fact: Einfeld v HIH Casualty and General Insurance Ltd (1999) 166 ALR 714  (allegation about the effect of lack of timely notice on the enforceability of an insurance contract). Additionally, in Spies v Commonwealth Bank of Australia (1991) 24 NSWLR 691 at 698–9 , it was held that pleadings involved an implied representation that the party filing the pleading believed it had a prospect of success;
